87
00:06:27,640 --> 00:06:31,720
And so this evening, as we look at this first aspect of a longing for peace, notice as we

88
00:06:31,720 --> 00:06:38,140
begin reading the Psalm, in verse number one, the Bible says, unto thee, O Lord, do I lift

89
00:06:38,140 --> 00:06:39,760
up my soul.

90
00:06:40,239 --> 00:06:43,640
Oh my God, I trust in thee.

91
00:06:43,640 --> 00:06:45,179
Let me not be ashamed.

92
00:06:45,179 --> 00:06:48,600
Let not mine enemies triumph over me.

93
00:06:48,600 --> 00:06:52,459
Yea, let none that wait on thee be ashamed.

94
00:06:52,459 --> 00:06:56,359
Let them be ashamed, which transgress without cause.

95
00:06:56,359 --> 00:07:00,079
We'll look at some additional verses as we get through the text this evening.

96
00:07:00,079 --> 00:07:04,720
But I want you to notice with me, first of all, that we see the distress of the Psalmist.

97
00:07:04,720 --> 00:07:09,940
We find that as you look at the Psalm, he begins, unto thee, O Lord, do I lift up my

98
00:07:09,940 --> 00:07:11,140
soul.

99
00:07:11,140 --> 00:07:15,579
He's declaring his trust and we see that he's in distress.

100
00:07:15,579 --> 00:07:17,679
He mentions the enemies in verse two.

101
00:07:17,679 --> 00:07:20,100
We'll see it again in verse number 19.

102
00:07:20,100 --> 00:07:24,579
And we begin to look at the distress of the Psalmist, and of course we know because we're

103
00:07:24,579 --> 00:07:31,540
reading the Psalm, that David here verbalizes the fact that he's dealing with enemies.

104
00:07:31,540 --> 00:07:37,660
He verbalizes the condition, the circumstances that he's dealing with.

105
00:07:37,660 --> 00:07:42,320
And for you and I this evening, it's a good thing for us to be able to verbalize what

106
00:07:42,320 --> 00:07:46,459
